# Unratified — Marketing, User Journey, and UX Strategy

## Core Audiences (Established 2026-03-02)

Three core audiences, derived from the higher-order differential analysis findings. The analysis itself points to these groups: technical analysts who can evaluate the methodology, educators who shape the judgment pipeline, and academics who extend and validate the work.

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                        THREE CORE AUDIENCES                          │
│                                                                      │
│  ┌──────────────────┐  ┌──────────────────┐  ┌──────────────────┐   │
│  │                  │  │                  │  │                  │   │
│  │  HACKERS         │  │  TEACHERS        │  │  SCIENTISTS      │   │
│  │                  │  │                  │  │                  │   │
│  │  observatory.    │  │  unratified.org  │  │  observatory.    │   │
│  │  unratified.org  │  │  /educators      │  │  unratified.org  │   │
│  │                  │  │                  │  │                  │   │
│  │  "Show me the    │  │  "Give me        │  │  "Show me the    │   │
│  │   analysis"      │  │   materials"     │  │   methodology"   │   │
│  │                  │  │                  │  │                  │   │
│  │  Evaluates:      │  │  Evaluates:      │  │  Evaluates:      │   │
│  │  rigor, novelty, │  │  usability,      │  │  citations,      │   │
│  │  intellectual    │  │  curriculum fit,  │  │  reproducibility,│   │
│  │  honesty        │  │  classroom-ready  │  │  novel contrib.  │   │
│  └──────────────────┘  └──────────────────┘  └──────────────────┘   │
│                                                                      │
│  WHY THESE THREE:                                                    │
│  • Hackers: evaluate + amplify the analysis (distribution)           │
│  • Teachers: shape the judgment pipeline (Article 13 pivot)          │
│  • Scientists: validate + extend the methodology (credibility)       │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

### Future Audience: Commercial Educational Publishers

A fourth audience exists as a future possibility, distinct from the three core audiences above. Commercial educational publishers — textbook companies, EdTech platforms, curriculum distributors — may want to license and package this content for institutional distribution. This audience requires a separate licensing conversation before activation: the current CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 content license blocks commercial use by design. See Audience 4 section below for full persona.

### Why NOT a general public audience

The analysis shows that the general public arrives through one of these three channels, not independently. Attempting to serve "everyone" dilutes the content for the audiences who actually engage with it. General public reach comes as a second-order effect: teachers bring it to students, HN amplifies it to the broader tech community, academic citations bring it to policy circles.

