                    │    │
                    │    │
                    │    │  unratified.org/educators
                    │    │  (Teachers)
                    │    ★
                    │    │
                    └────┘

  Other players:
  ○ CESR — high analytical depth, low public engagement
  ○ Amnesty — high advocacy directness, low analytical depth
  ○ AAAS Right to Science — moderate both, academic-only
  ○ United for Human Rights — low depth, high accessibility

  Unratified occupies the space between:
  deep analysis (observatory) ←→ practical action (main site + educators)
```

---

## Key Messaging by Audience (Final)

### HN: Lead with the methodology
> "Seven hypotheses about AI's economic impact. A consensus/parsimony discriminator. One composite model survives. And it accidentally makes the strongest case for a 1966 UN treaty you've never heard of."

### Teachers: Lead with the materials
> "Ready-to-use lesson plans connecting AI's economic transformation to human rights — backed by original research, designed for your classroom."

### Academics: Lead with the novel contribution
> "A differential diagnosis framework applied to AI economic impact, with integral chain analysis connecting Jevons paradox and bottleneck migration to ICESCR obligations under Article 15."
